results.notes:
On HCL+ sandstone bedrock in Juniper scrub south-facing hillside with Acarospora strigata, A. socialis, A. macrospora, many Caloplaca species, Staurothere, Candelariella, etc.

Thallus is tiny, nearly black, lacking cortex, areolate to subsquamulose, granulose, with urceolate apothecia. The apothecia are small, up to 0.5mm, with a thalline margin containing packets of blue-green algae with a red sheath that reacts K+reddish. Cells at thallus margin are reddish brown. There are POL+ crystals in the marginal cells, and white crystals in the hypothecium. But none of these tiny black species actually have secondary substances, so who knows what the polarizing filters were picking up. Paraphyses and asci conglutinated. Hymenium K/I+Blue. Spores 8/ascus, not well developed, simple, hyaline, about 11×5-6µm.

There are a number of small black cyanolichens that fit this general look, but Pyrenopsis is the only one I could find with the K+R (lit says purplish) reaction. No modern treatment for NA is available.

results.notes:
Growing in moss under a large beech, with 2-3 mature oaks in the immediate vicinity. This organism has been fruiting there with little interruption throughout the summer, producing only 1-3 fruitbodies at a time. This is the same little patch of land where I’ve been finding most mycorrhizals on this property. My guess, this has to be the same species & organism as those of obs 328145 and obs 373449 – despite the somewhat variable morphology – both of which were found at this exact spot. This post and #328145 look identical, with their dark brown colors and prominent and heavy stipital reticulation, while the smooth-stiped and purplish-brown #373449, which was recently sequenced (DNA data are yet to be posted & discussed), looks more like T. badiceps. BTW, the full-length ITS of #373449 (632 bps long) doesn’t match anything in GenBank, and the recovered accessions have low similarities and query covers. Furhtermore, there are no ITS sequenced labeled as T. badiceps in GenBank.
